Well, yeah, I'm just saying that, you know, life is a summation of all the experiences and what they meant to you, I think.
And I have been as fortunate a person as ever has been born in that I've got relationships in my college days that, frankly, most of them have been because of A&M since I graduated.
And I'm talking about local A&M clubs.
Again, I mentioned before, any church, you meet A&M people, you met people.
I know people because I saw a ring across the room somewhere.
I've been here at Granbury.
I moved down here recently.
I see those rings and walk over, and it's an entree.
You walk over there, and you're not meeting a stranger.
You don't feel like you are, and you feel very comfortable in that.
It's given me, in my personal life, an opportunity to accomplish a lot outside the economic realm.
And that means serving A&M in the best way that I know how and up, frankly, maybe exceeding my level of capability, associating with former students, to give you an example.
How in the world would you feel ever up to serving as the president of the Association of Former Students?
You represent 200,000 people who feel about it like I do, or at least most of us do.
It's been an experience for our family towards a social environment.
It would not be anything else.
I'm not sending out many things that are rewarding in your life, because we all participate in those, because we all do.
But Bo and I, it's a major outlet in our personal lives.
Without it, we would be a far less rich life.
It's given us an opportunity to expose our son to Texas A&M in the time he was a squirt, all the way to where he graduated with it.
with the experience that I've had.
And he's very dedicated to that.
He feels very similar to it than I do.
And he will have a richer life than I do.
So it's meant, next to our faith and our family, Texas A&M is right in there with what's important to us.
And it's because of what has contributed to the life, to our life.
And I don't think that there's any way to repay that adequately.
Is there anything that I haven't touched on that you want to... Well, first off, I appreciate you doing this.
Don't worry about it.
I think that you made a point.
You know, history's a great teacher, but you've got to record it first.
It doesn't serve the purpose of this, but not... And my contribution, of course, is minimal, but there's some people who are renowned who you'll be interviewing who have experiences that are
as rich for them as mine has been for me, but their profile is high.
You see, and what I worry about too, nobody keeps a diary anymore.
We don't write personal letters much anymore.
We don't write personal letters.
And when those people are no more, their memory will be gone.
Like Aquarius, we missed all that.
Somebody needs to talk to Herbie.
But Mrs.
Rudder, John Colviss, all kinds of folks like that.
That's so important.
Because like you say, there's not a good record of those things like in the past, but people don't write things, they email or they call the department, they phone.
